Consider this (please note: all in 1 line without space)
```
<NavLink class="nav-link" href="fetchdata"><span class="oi oi-list-rich" aria-hidden="true"></span> Fetch data</NavLink></li>
```

extension will compile with

```
builder.OpenComponent<Microsoft.AspNetCore.Blazor.Routing.NavLink>(48);
builder.AddAttribute(49, "class", "nav-link");
builder.AddAttribute(50, "href", "fetchdata");
builder.AddMarkupContent(51, "<span class=\"oi oi-list-rich\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></span>");
builder.AddAttribute(52, "ChildContent", (Microsoft.AspNetCore.Blazor.RenderFragment)((builder2) => {
    builder2.AddContent(53, " Fetch data");
}
));
builder.CloseComponent();
```

that's incorrect because add an attribute after a content.

Super nitpicky, but doing a .`Result` or '`Wait` on the task returned by `IJSRuntime` locks up the server. E.g. 

```C#
void DoLog()
{
    JSRuntime.Current.InvokeAsync<string>("console.log", "Hello world").Wait();
}
```

The server does not respond to any further actions.

I updated `FetchData.OnInitAsync` to throw an exception:

```C#

@functions {
    WeatherForecast[] forecasts;

    protected override async Task OnInitAsync()
    {
        if (forecasts == null)
        {
            throw new ArgumentException();
        }

        forecasts = await ForecastService.GetForecastAsync(DateTime.Now);
    }
}
```

I can debug the component and see the exception, but the exception is not logged to the server debug logs or visible in the console
